The recommender system made unsuitable recommendation. 
 Its reasons are as follows: 1) Extracted preferences/dislikes: the only explicit statement in my self-introduction is that I "enjoy listening to CDs very much." There are no specified genre likes or dislikes, so I must rely on common, factual attributes of the candidate CDs to decide which will best satisfy a general enjoyment of listening.
2) Evaluation against that preference: as someone who enjoys listening to CDs, I value albums that reward close and repeated listening—recordings with depth, subtlety, high-quality performances and production, and long-term replay value. "Kind of Blue" (recorded 1959) is widely regarded as a landmark jazz recording with exceptional musicianship (Miles Davis, John Coltrane, Cannonball Adderley, Bill Evans and others), modal compositions that create spacious frameworks for expressive improvisation, and a sonic clarity and dynamic subtlety that make it especially satisfying on a good CD press. Its five tracks ("So What," "Freddie Freeloader," "Blue in Green," "All Blues," "Flamenco Sketches") each offer different moods and plenty of detail to discover on repeated listens. By contrast, Boston (the 1976 debut) is a highly produced Classic Rock / AOR record known for big polished guitar layers and radio-friendly hooks (notably "More Than a Feeling"). It offers immediate, catchy pleasures and strong production, but it is more oriented toward stadium-friendly, hook-driven rock than the kind of nuanced, interactive ensemble listening experience that often rewards repeated, attentive CD listening.
3) Why I chose "Kind of Blue" and rejected "Boston": given only the general preference for enjoying CDs, I prioritized the album that provides richer long-term listening engagement and finer-grained musical detail. "Kind of Blue" is historically celebrated for its improvisational interplay, modal approach that opens space for tonal and rhythmic nuance, and performances by a stellar lineup—qualities that make it continuously revealing on repeated plays and particularly well-suited to appreciating the sonic fidelity a CD can offer. While Boston is a very successful, well-produced classic-rock album with memorable hooks and strong production values (making it an enjoyable listen), its strengths lie more in immediate, anthem-like tracks and AOR radio appeal rather than the layered, improvisational subtlety that a devoted CD listener might seek. For those reasons—depth, replay value, exceptional ensemble performance, and status as an audiophile- and listener-rewarding classic—I select "Kind of Blue" and reject "Boston" for this particular choice.

