  - The description’s “tactile, intimate remasters” also risks the over‑intimate character I warned against if it narrows stereo layering or reduces room for rhythmic punch, even though transients are said to be preserved.
Conclusion: Because original sequencing, preserved headroom and authentic late‑70s AOR album craft are non‑negotiable priorities for me, the Original 1976 AOR mix best aligns with my preferences. Turn It On Again: The Hits may sound good track‑by‑track, but its hits‑anthology format and potential loss of album context conflict with my core dislikes, so I reject it in favor of the original 1976 AOR mix.

