 Its reasons are as follows: Extracted preferences/dislikes: I prefer late‑’70s/early‑’80s AOR and hook‑forward pop/rock with guitar‑driven, jangly or layered electric guitars, tight multi‑tracked harmony vocals, and melody‑first arrangements; spare, punchy mixes, propulsive synth‑bass when it serves the hook, wide stereo imaging, tactile midrange and expressive electric solos. I prize cohesive single‑disc sequencing of full‑length tracks, restrained remasters that keep headroom, micro‑dynamics and separation, and punchy controlled bass/transients. I dislike hits‑only or scattershot anthologies and truncated edits, radio‑bright or over‑compressed mastering that flattens midrange nuance, over‑intimate close‑mic vocals that collapse stereo width, ballad‑heavy sequencing that kills momentum, and piano‑first intimate small‑group jazz aesthetics lacking layered electric arrangements.
Why Back in Black wins: Back in Black is a single, cohesive album from 1980 with concise riff sequencing and full‑length tracks — that satisfies my preference for album flow over a hits anthology. Its core attributes line up strongly with the sonic traits I prize: guitar‑driven, attack‑first riffs with tactile guitar bite and a tactile midrange; locked, punchy bass/drums and tight low end that preserve transients; and analog warmth plus dynamics‑preserving mastering that retains headroom and micro‑dynamics. Those elements match my preference for spare, punchy mixes and controlled transients rather than radio‑bright, over‑compressed mastering. Even though AC/DC’s vocals are gravelly and upfront rather than multi‑tracked harmony leads, they sit with the rhythm rather than collapsing stereo imaging, which is preferable to over‑intimate close‑mic presentation. Overall, the album’s visceral, guitar‑forward, dynamics‑preserving presentation aligns better with my stated priorities for midrange presence, punch, and cohesive album sequencing.
Why I reject the Curated Eurythmics Greatest Hits: The Eurythmics package hits several technical boxes I like — propulsive synth‑bass, tasteful remastering that preserves micro‑dynamics, clear instrument separation, and hook‑focused sequencing — but it is a greatest‑hits compilation. I explicitly said I dislike hits‑only or scattershot anthologies unless they preserve album flow; a “Curated Greatest Hits” is still fundamentally a hits collection and is therefore a less desirable format than a single cohesive album of full‑length tracks. Additionally, Annie Lennox’s vocals being “pushed upfront” risks the over‑intimate, close‑mic vocal presentation I dislike if it collapses stereo width; the Eurythmics emphasis on synth/lead vocals also moves away from my core preference for layered electric‑guitar arrangements and multi‑tracked harmony vocals. In short, while the Eurythmics remaster and hooks are attractive, the compilation format and vocal/front‑of‑mix presentation make it less aligned with my priorities than Back in Black.

